    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing leaves on the bottom of the stems, a common issue in tomato plants, can be due to several factors, including underwatering, overwatering, nutrient deficiencies, or root bound conditions. It's possible that the roots have become waterlogged, causing the lower leaves to turn yellow and drop. To address this, ensure the soil drains well and provide supplemental calcium or magnesium, as these are essential nutrients for tomato plants. You can also inspect the roots to see if they've become root bound and consider transplanting the plant to give the roots more room to grow.",
